segments.text: The measure of congeniality, another person might characterize it as weakness, that in my relationship to Scott and White, that I did not insist on the classical control by academia of the clinic.
That was a crucial issue and it still is and it isn't necessary.
It can be gotten around.
Am I correct in feeling that both you and Dr. Brindley were trying to figure out how to make it work?
Yes, sir.
This is self-revisionism or self-whatever, but there is no question that that was the attitude 100% of the time.
That's what I always thought.
Yes.
And...

here on the campus did you feel that was the attitude of Chancellor Williams and President Miller and Vice President Prescott absolutely absolutely I think they would have agreed to anything that I had proposed they were so anxious I don't anxious is not the right word enthusiastic I don't want to use anxious because it conveys a certain
In the early months of your work with Scott and White, do you remember any specific examples of Dr. Brindley's help?
It was more subtle than that.
He was such a towering figure at Scott and White that merely the evidence that he wanted to make it work was sufficient.
I think that

that very likely someone other than Dr. Brindley, I don't know the past history of the institution very much, but subsequently I don't think anyone else could have carried it off with the authority, and by authority I mean the personality authority, the personal authority that Dr. Brindley had that made it work.
And his influence with the trustees, I think he was the kingpin.
Was Olin Teague still our congressman?
No, but Oliver Meadows was another person, incidentally, whom you might, I don't know whether Oliver is still alive.
He was ranching up in North Texas.
Oliver Meadows was the administrative assistant to Olin Teague.
And I think Oliver Meadows probably was the genius behind the establishment of five new medical schools under the auspices of the Veterans Administration.
And we were one of those five.
Indeed.
That's Oliver Meadows.
And he has never received recognition for that, incidentally.
Teague, of course, would do whatever his administrative assistant told him to do, like any good congressman.
Were there, as you were working with the VA hospital up there, who were the key people that you worked with?
I remember one or two, but I don't remember their names.
There was one physician who was important, Julian Acker, who is dead now, cancer of the lung, he smoked a pipe and that sort of thing.
But there was a senior administrator.
In the VA system, there's a lay administrator who's really in charge.
The VA entered into the relationship with a good deal of suspicion, feeling among other things that we were a VA medical school and they should be running things.
And they had a long time tense relationship with Scott and White.
A certain number of the Scott and White physicians were consultants at the VA.
There was an enormous gradient of, what shall I say, skepticism about the quality of medicine as between Scott and White and the VA hospital, with some justification probably at that time.
So the VA hospital was uncomfortable with the relationship with Scott and White assuming the senior role, as it were.
Soon after you got here, did you develop a kind of a game plan as to what you were, step by step, what you were going to try to do?
I think so, probably.
I never wrote it down.
Can you describe kind of what it was?
Well, I wanted very much, and this proved to not be doable.
I wanted the medical school to be part of the university.
That's a cliche, but I swear I wanted that.
And it did not work.
And it did not work over again some traditional, highly traditional academic values on the part of faculty members, both here on campus and in the medical school.

I wanted very much to have, just to be more integrated I guess really with the rest of the university than the respective colleges are in the university, more than agriculture or engineering or science or whatever.
I thought that could be done and that was part of a fairly popular current.
at that time in medical education.
Never really accomplished.
One of the convincing, one of the reasons that the LCME moved favorably on this medical school was that it was to be on the university campus.
It wasn't going to be in Dallas.
It was to be on the campus.
And that didn't work out.
In trying to make it work, who were your best allies?
I suppose Dr. Prescott and I don't remember the others.
Were there any deans that were?

No, no the deans the deans the ones that are most relevant wanted to take over let's say chemistry biochemistry wanted to take over biochemistry in a medical school or the like and always veterinary medicine was very
How shall I say that in the least prejudicial way?
Very skeptical.
I don't remember whether you had a veterinary school at Missouri or not.
You did.
Well, perhaps by the time you were there, they were good buddies.
They were that close together, too.
But that was not a comfortable relationship.
All right.
So one of the things you had to work on quickly

was the second year yes and then the clinical yes describe describe how that came about well i don't i at that time in in medical education and maybe also in the university deans could be a lot more autocratic than they can now
And so I don't remember that we, we didn't have any votes about it, I'll tell you that.
We didn't have a discussion as to whether or not we should affiliate with Scott and White and send students up there.
All right.
Was there enough space here on the campus for the first and second years?
Yes.
Okay.
Yes.
And they primarily in the Teague and where else?
I don't remember.
I know subsequently we got the old Creamery.
But I don't remember, oh I know, in the, what was the old chemistry building, what's the name of that, quite an old building, but it was chemistry.
We had space in there, kind of reluctant, and I must say that when I went around looking for space I didn't find a lot of cooperation among deans, there was nobody.
They'd be glad to take over, but they weren't willing to give up space to do it.
And who were some of your first key hires, your key additions?
Very few, because they had essentially all been hired.
Everybody was up at Scott and White, and the key people were down here.
So I can't claim to have made any key hires.
Do you remember when you first went to the legislature to...
do any lobbying?

Well, while Dr. Miller was president and Mac Prescott, I had no problem in talking with the, I get confused, I've been in enough states, I think it was the BEF, is there a BEF in Texas, Board of Educational Finance?
Coordinating Board.
Coordinating Board, but
But the staff, what was the staff called?
Okay, anyhow, I could go to them and talk to them privately and tell them what we needed.
But with Jarvis's resignation, there were barriers set up immediately.
I could no longer freelance as I had in Oregon and particularly in New Mexico.
New Mexico, I got a cancer center established there.
A million dollars was an enormous amount of money in New Mexico, and at that time, and I went before the legislature, president didn't impede me or anything, go to it, anything you can get, get.
And I said, we need a million dollars, we'll get matching funds, we'll get three to one matching funds.
And one of the legislators asked me, said, look, I'm all enthused about this, it's a lot of money, but I want to know what you're going to do with that building when we have a cure for cancer.
And that was a serious inquiry.
He was doing his job.
Don't we wish that question had become appropriate?
Yes.

But the point of the anecdote is that in Oregon, to a lesser extent, but in a place like New Mexico where I'd had most of my experience, I had free entree to the legislature, to the staff, and at first down here I did.

with the staff who were the people who were most influential I don't mean to uh... but oh and you know I got a lot of help from uh... from uh... Billy Clayton he was a big help uh... yes or or he had I'm not sure of the timing precisely but uh... he was a big help and then subsequently from the uh... uh... the the vice governor the deputy governor
Who?
Lieutenant Governor.
Lieutenant Governor.
The giant, Bullock.
Oh, Bob Bullock.
Oh, well, Hobby, too.
We got good help from Hobby.
Hobby and Bullock and Bill Clayton were very supportive.
And you know another guy who was supportive, although skeptical, I mean, playing his role of skepticism, was Ken Ashworth.
Are you going to talk with Ken or talk with him?
No, I want to very much.
Yes.

were there any key now your program of people that you're talking to is this based on some mortality table well I am trying to talk to senior people you've talked to Mack have you yes in that first year as you're getting ready for the students
for year three and four to move up to Temple.
You worked with Dr. Brindley.
What arrangements were made up there for them in the first years?
We were able to persuade the Veterans Administration to clean out, that was a cantonment hospital, to empty a couple of buildings and turn them into student quarters.
And we did not require that the students live there, but they were very grateful for the opportunity.
The VA did a splendid job of fixing up those living quarters for the students.
Was that arrangement to have both the VA and Scott and White, was that comparatively special for the Indian Medical School?
In a sense it was, but in a sense it was not.

the somewhere right after world war ii the end of world war ii the veterans administration was beleaguered by people who were skeptical about the quality of care and so they established dean's committees at the at all of the virtually all of the va hospitals and dean chaired that committee and it was really an oversight committee
It was a board, a medical board for the VA hospital.
So they were familiar with that.
And they were familiar from other VA hospitals with the way universities and medical schools

appointed their department heads chairman as the heads of the services in the VA hospitals it was resented but it was familiar but here we were coming into an established rather tense relationship and suddenly saying to them okay from now on the chairman of surgery at Scott and White is going to be the chief at surgery at the VA hospital
and is going to be on the dean's committee.
So that was resented.
And that was new.
And in general, they took that fairly well because we had the leverage in Washington.
They got direction from Washington.
Are there some people at the VA who, in hindsight now, deserve compliments for making it work?

some people in Temple I think only Julian Acker the and the typical student A&M medical student spent about how much time at Scott and White compared to VA I can't be precise I would say it might have been two-thirds at the time at Scott and White it's a little distorted because of course the VA hospital had no pediatrics and no OB-GYN
So naturally they had those at Scott & White.
The psychiatry service was much more current at Scott & White than at the VA where the issue was old men dying of emphysema and cancer of the lung, alcoholics.
Can you share with this machine any examples of specific events or incidents about
The beginning up there, serious or humorous?
Well, nothing comes to mind, Haskell.
Nothing where something in the middle of the road stopped or went dead or somebody called?
No.
So that first class up there, approximately 24?
Yes.
In number.
And do you remember how many of those graduated?
All of them.
Was that unusual?
No.
That's not unusual nationally?
I would say not again given the context of a new medical school with a very small class.
No, I don't think so.
And then when did the numbers increase per class?
Only after I left.
I guess we went to 36 reluctantly.
I was strongly opposed and am still opposed to increasing the class size.
I had another one of my illusions was that we could have an elitist medical school.
My paradigm was Dartmouth, which historically had been the first two years for Harvard, to a lesser extent for Yale.
And always had had 24 students, of course.
Under that dream, would ours have gone somewhere for their third and fourth year?
No, to Scott and White.
That would have been all right.
That would have been acceptable.
But to keep a very small student body and to have very close attention to everything about them.
As you were planning it,
what was going to be special about this medical school?

I would guess in the first instance and the biggest disappointment was it would be part of the university and I guess secondly was the pressure within the there was pressure within the basic science faculty here to get bigger they couldn't understand why I didn't want to get larger why I didn't want more students
Why did they want it bigger?
Because everything is better if it's bigger.

The other disappointment that I had but I had anticipated this and knew it would really be a struggle was in the development of a true research program at Scott and White and to have them put a value and I mean now a financial value really on research in other words to be willing to give

an individual twenty five percent of his time free that he didn't have to produce income clinical income to do research were you planning on these students these twenty four or so students were they also going to be elite and quality well yeah I hope so how were we going to recruit those in large measure because of having twenty four students or thirty six students and we did that at the beginning we did
We quickly became competitive, and there are some fine medical schools here, I mean in Texas.
Am I not correct that they did quite well on their national?
Absolutely, outstanding, outstanding.
And we got the standard response from the other faculties of the other medical schools where you're teaching them to the examination.
Well, we can't do that.
We were teaching them.
And they had confidence, and they knew what they knew.

And another thing that I felt, and here I got a little bit of a problem with the students to some extent, and this was a negative factor in recruiting students, students who went to Bentaube, I mean, Baylor, Bentaube or to, what's the big hospital in Dallas?
Baylor.
No.
Parkland.
Students there knew that in their junior year they were going to do brain surgery.

And students knew that they came to Texas A&M and Scott and White, what they were going to do in their third year was some blood counts and examine a patient under the supervision of an experienced doctor and tell them what was going on.
The student was going to be a student, not a young doctor.
And that was a negative.
But that was another thing in my old-fashioned mind was that students were students and should be students.
Here in Bryan College Station, what was the attitude of Scott and White and the other medical... Well, Scott and White...
I would say that St. Joseph
Maybe in the person of Sister, what's her name?
Kiwi, what's her name?
Sister something or other.
Krenz, Kunz, Kunz, Kunz or something.

They didn't quite understand why we didn't immediately open up to them, why we didn't just appoint their doctors as professors and send the medical students over, feeling that they could just as well be educated at, they didn't understand, simply did not understand that.

and that's common when you put a medical school in a new environment all the doctors in town think that they're professors and they'll teach the students the real stuff were there some Brazos County doctors that were particularly positive in being members of the A&M medical team only subsequently O.C.
was one one who was kind of a missed blessing was Harry Lipscomb
He'd been on the faculty at Baylor when Baylor was very much a clinical school and still had those values.
He was of the same vintage then of Phil Davis when the local doctors were the medical school.
There were one or two like that.
Others were just kind of indifferent.
We didn't have much in the way of the overt hostility that we found in
at UCLA particularly but also in Albuquerque where there was real hostility.

The principal reservation that the medical community of Texas not alone of College Station had about a relationship with Scott and White was that Scott and White was a pinko organization because it was a group practice and group practice was borderline communistic.

the was Scott and White almost unanimously supportive no no no no no but again they didn't get to vote on it they were really given the they were given the option the physicians of either being part of the teaching program or not and virtually everybody opted to be part of the teaching program and they quickly became

proprietary looking back on those years what did medical education under your direction here what did A&M do best and then what did it do least best in medicine the transition from Jarvis and Mac to the succeeding hierarchies

was not good and I attributed it to the fact that the senior administrators had had no experience with medical education before had no concept of the way in which I believe but I'll bet every dean in engineering or agriculture or whatever believes that we have a special culture I'm sure there's a special culture in engineering they were more used to that it seems to me that there was a

there was a could have been my paranoia but I really am pretty level headed about that resentment that doctors were rich and that we should have that really what we ought to have is a national health care system and that somehow we were a plutocratic organization and arrogant
and condescending.
Some of that was probably true, but that was difficult.

I think that it would have been better if the several presidents and vice presidents had had four or five years at the University of Missouri first or wherever and knew what accommodations could be made
to medicine and what the opportunities were.
What we missed, we just so badly missed it, was an appreciation of the value that a medical school could bring to a university campus.
I think that was never understood.
Can you think of any examples of where
an opportunity was missed because of that lack of understanding?
I guess they were aborted so early.
They were in a pre-embryo state.
Were you part of the planning of the new medical building across the tracks?
Oh yes, yes.
Describe how that came about.
There had developed during that time

a paradigm for basic medical sciences buildings they were to be multifunctional laboratories were to be multifunctional and we pretty much fit into that mold I did not have the leverage that I believed that I should have with the architects the architects were similarly inexperienced in medical education and really did not listen well
And the buildings and grounds people, whatever the hell, colonel, general, whatever, some guy who ran that thing, of course knew what buildings should be.
No concept at all about a medical school.
And so we were constrained, I think, in the design more than we should have been.
General Peeler.
Yes, yes, yes.
Now you see for some reason that didn't happen at UCLA and it didn't happen at New Mexico.
Somehow people there were more freewheeling or maybe I well and certainly in New Mexico I had an opportunity to be part of and to observe it and participate less so because I was so junior at UCLA.
But those, well, UCLA, the president at UCLA at that time was Murphy, who was a physician, subsequently became chairman of the board of the Los Angeles Times.
And at New Mexico, we had Mr. Popejoy, who had no doctorate, was Mr. Popejoy, and he was a Williams, a kindly old gentleman, benevolent,
wonderful, supportive, a whole different kind of old-fashioned way of doing things.
If you could have planned the building entirely as you wanted it, what would that medical facility have included that it does not?
What would you have done differently?
I think I know I would have wanted more commons area for the students.
I would have wanted it to be more congenial from the standpoint of students lounging around and talking to each other and interacting with each other and to some extent with the faculty.
Even something in the way of a snack bar, of something to soften it in that way.
What about in terms of its facilities?

construction and laboratory not that bad we probably would have arranged them differently but kind of cut and dried I mean out of somebody's book as the building was constructed it was designed for classes of what size I think 48 I believe and we're now at 64 yeah so theoretically we're yes there was another thing happening

not alone in our medical school in medical education with the animal rights people and sentimentality and that kind of thing the nature of laboratories changed physiology particularly so that the needs and demands on laboratories were much less and even the conviction
in medical education that students ought to experience.
There was a better, there was more utilization of, it wasn't, it was the advent of computers or of simulated experiments and the like rather than the actual hands-on doing of experiments.
So that those changes in medical education have made it doable to have 64 students in there.
It's become somewhat more didactic.
